blocked by the newly arrived USS Monitor. The clash of ironclads was underway. After fighting for nine hours, both ships withdrew, neither seriously damaged, with both sides claiming victory. Although the battle may have been a draw and the Monitor sank in a storm later that year, this first encounter between powered, ironclad warships spelled the end of wooden warships—and the dawn of a new navy. This book takes a new look at this historic battle. The ten original essays, written by leading historians, explore every aspect of the battle—from the building of the warships and life aboard these “iron coffins” to tactics, strategy, and the debates about who really won the battle of Hampton Roads. Co-published with The Mariners’ Museum, home to the USS Monitor Center, this authoritative guide to the military, political, technological, and cultural dimensions of this historic battle also features a portfolio of classic lithographs, drawings, and paintings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aHISTORY / Military / United States.2bisacsh1 aDavis, William C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuller, Howard J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGutierrez, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHightower, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolzer, Harold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolzer, Harold, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJohnston, Jeff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMindell, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMulligan, Tim, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aQuarstein, John V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id